# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1911-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1911-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1911-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1911-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1911-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1911-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1911-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1911-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1911-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1911-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The **1911 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1911 season.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The eighth edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion New York Giants.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The Athletics won the best-of-seven series four games to two, in a rematch of the 1905 World Series, getting revenge over the Giants, who had won in their previous meeting.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Philadelphia third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker earned his nickname during this Series.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] His home run in Game 2 off Rube Marquard was the margin of victory for the Athletics, and his blast in Game 3 off Christy Mathewson tied that game in the ninth inning, and the Athletics eventually won in the 11th.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Ironically, Mathewson (or his ghostwriter) had criticized Marquard in his newspaper column after Game 2 for giving up the gopher ball, only to fall victim himself the very next day.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Baker was swinging a hot bat in general, going 9 for 24 to lead all batters in the Series with a .375 average.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] According to his obituary in *The New York Times* (July 28, 1971), Giants catcher Chief Meyers threw out 12 runners, creating a record for the most assists by a catcher during the World Series.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The six consecutive days of rain between Games 3 and 4 caused the longest delay between World Series games until the earthquake-interrupted 1989 World Series (which incidentally featured the same two franchises, albeit on the West Coast, and which also resulted in an A's victory over the Giants).
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] With the sixth and final game being played on October 26, this was also the latest-ending World Series by calendar date until 1981.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] This was the second time in World Series history that two teams met in a World Series rematch.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The first time was when the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers met in consecutive years, in 1907 and 1908.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] This is also the first World Series to feature two teams that had previously won a title.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The Athletics were the defending champions while the Giants had won in 1905.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] early risers at 9 am at the Shibe Park box office at 21st and Lehigh...
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] With a perfect top of the first, Christy Mathewson set the record with 28 straight shutout innings in World Series play, a record that would be broken by Boston Red Sox's Babe Ruth with 29+2⁄3 innings in the 1918 World Series.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Mathewson's postseason record for consecutive scoreless innings against one team would not be broken until 2013 when the Detroit Tigers' Justin Verlander shut out the Athletics (now playing in Oakland) for 30 consecutive innings in the 2012 and 2013 ALDS.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] With the score tied at 1 and with Eddie Collins on second, Frank Baker blasted a two-run home run off Rube Marquard to deep right field for the go ahead score and the Athletics held on to win game 2, 3–1.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] With the Giants up 1–0 going into the ninth with Mathewson on the mound, it appeared the series was going to be 2–1 New York.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] But with one out, Baker stepped up to the plate and blasted his second home run in as many games to tie it at 1.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Thus, the nickname "Home Run" Baker was born.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Two innings later with the score still tied at 1, Baker singled and scored on an error to make it 3–1.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The Giants rallied for one run in the bottom half but the game ended with a runner being thrown out on a stolen base attempt.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] After six days of rain, the series resumed.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Chief Bender, after giving up two runs in the first, shut out the Giants the rest of the way on his way to a 4–2 win and 3–1 series lead.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] On the verge of elimination, the Giants fought back.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] They tied it at 3 with two runs in the bottom of the ninth, and then won it with a run in the tenth when Larry Doyle scored on a sacrifice fly.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Home plate umpire Bill Klem later said Doyle had failed to touch home plate after sliding in.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Since none of the Athletics noticed this and Philadelphia failed to appeal, Klem had to let the winning run stand.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Josh Devore became the first player to get a game-tying hit in the World Series with his team one out from elimination, a feat that would not be repeated until Otis Nixon in the 1992 World Series.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] Bender threw a 4-hitter to clinch the series, the Athletics second consecutive World Series title.
[src:1911-world-series/1911-world-series] The A's pitching staff held the Giants to a .175 team batting average, lowest ever for a 6-game series.
[src:1911-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1911-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
